  "Question": "<p>So, I'm not a big expert in this subject but I know <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_236\"><math alttext=\"1+2+3...=-\\dfrac{1}{12}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>\u2062</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u2026</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo>-</mo><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>12</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> isn't to do with 'real' maths but it's all to do with the zeta function; however I was watching a maths video and the equation:</p> <p><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_237\"><math alttext=\"\\frac{x(x+1)}{2}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mfrac><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></semantics></math></span></p> <p>... is actually a perfect equation for the series <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_238\"><math alttext=\"1+2+3...\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>\u2062</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u2026</mi></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span> etc. where <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_239\"><math alttext=\"x\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>x</mi></semantics></math></span> represents <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_240\"><math alttext=\"n\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>n</mi></semantics></math></span> in a series and <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_241\"><math alttext=\"y\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>y</mi></semantics></math></span> is the sum of the series up to <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_242\"><math alttext=\"n\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>n</mi></semantics></math></span>. So, you can conclude that:</p> <p><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_243\"><math alttext=\"\\sum^{n}_{i=1}1+2+3...=\\frac{x(x+1)}{2}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mrow><msubsup><mo largeop=\"true\" symmetric=\"true\">\u2211</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>n</mi></msubsup><mn>1</mn></mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>\u2062</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">\u2026</mi></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>However, this is where it gets weird; as you have probably guessed, the roots of the equation is <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_244\"><math alttext=\"x=0,-1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span>  but if I want to find the integral of the roots from <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_245\"><math alttext=\"-1\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></semantics></math></span> to <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_246\"><math alttext=\"0\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mn>0</mn></semantics></math></span> which is under the <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_247\"><math alttext=\"x\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>x</mi></semantics></math></span> axis, I get the following:</p> <p><span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_248\"><math alttext=\"\\int_{-1}^{0}\\frac{x(x+1)}{2}\\&gt;dx=-\\frac{1}{12}\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><msubsup><mo largeop=\"true\" symmetric=\"true\">\u222b</mo><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mn>0</mn></msubsup><mrow><mpadded width=\"+2.2pt\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mpadded><mo>\u2062</mo><mrow><mo rspace=\"0pt\">\ud835\udc51</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>12</mn></mfrac></mrow></mrow></semantics></math></span></p> <p>So, my question is why is this the case; what connection is there between the value of the integral under the <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_249\"><math alttext=\"x\" class=\"ltx_Math\" display=\"inline\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mi>x</mi></semantics></math></span> axis that this graph has compared to the summation of the series?</p> <p><a href=\"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/d1k8kx4xuc\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Link to Desmos graph for more clarity</a></p>",
